I've thought about the question of when IMO problem formalizations should refer to graphs in the statement, yes, though I haven't written up any of my conclusions about what uniform formalization conventions for such problems might look like (and my thoughts on such questions evolved while I was writing formal statements for all the non-geometry 2024 shortlist problems, so some of those formalizations don't necessarily follow what I now think would be the best conventions - even apart from the differences between conventions for stating a problem on its own versus conventions for stating a problem when accompanied by a solution).

On the matter of graphs, my inclination is:
* if the problem explicitly refers to graphs (IMO 1991 P4) then of course use them in the formal statement;
* if the problem is essentially about graphs, just using different terminology rather than the word "graph" (e.g. IMO 2019 P3 or 2023 shortlist C7) then it's also appropriate to use them in the formal statement;
* but if the problem only incidentally involves some kind of adjacency relation, which could be expressed in terms of a graph but the problem isn't really a graph theory problem in shallow disguise (as with this problem), then it makes more sense to express it without graphs (of course a (human or AI) solver can translate into graphs for a solution if they wish);
* which is similar to the case of problems not even involving an adjacency relation (so obviously not expressed in terms of graphs) where graphs are nevertheless useful in solving the problem (e.g. IMO 2020 P3, which is convenient to solve using Eulerian circuits on multigraphs - not in mathlib at present, I think - but where nothing like that appears in the statement).

I don't, however, think that `SimpleGraph.Walk` would make things any simpler. I considered joining smaller pieces (via having a structure that only requires adjacency but doesn't constrain the end points), but defining such pieces would still require either a custom inductive definition to build a piece of length N (say), or use of `ofFn` (which is built on the inductive `Fin.foldr`) in defining the pieces, and anything involving composing multiple custom inductive definitions is likely to end up more complicated (with local API needed for each inductive definition) than just defining each path using `ofFn` applied to a function defined directly with `if` and then letting the automation of `split_ifs <;> simp <;> omega` deal with proving adjacency everywhere. And `List` has much more existing API to take advantage of in the statement and solution than `Walk` does.

You could of course try formalizing a non-graph-theory problem with adjacency (e.g. IMO 2022 P6 or IMO 2023 P5) in a way using mathlib graphs and see how it turns out; it's not what I think of as the most natural way to state such a problem, but such problems admit lots of different approaches to stating them formally.
